# Flutter Blade Clash Game Development Rules

## Project Overview
This project converts the existing HTML/JS "Blade Clash" game ([index.html](mdc:index.html)) into a native Flutter application following the architecture documented in [README.md](mdc:README.md).

## Architecture Principles
- **No External Dependencies**: Pure Dart/Flutter implementation
- **No Code Generation**: Avoid build_runner, json_annotation, etc.
- **Compact Structure**: Minimal file structure with clear separation of concerns
- **Low Coupling**: Each component should be independent and testable

## File Structure
```
lib/
├── main.dart                 # App entry point
├── models/                   # Plain Dart Objects (PDOs)
│   ├── character.dart        # Player and enemy models
│   ├── enemy_type.dart       # Enemy type definitions
│   ├── collectable.dart      # Collectible blade model
│   └── particle.dart         # Particle effect model
├── screens/
│   └── game_screen.dart      # Main game screen (StatefulWidget)
├── widgets/                  # Reusable UI components
│   ├── game_canvas.dart      # Core rendering (CustomPaint)
│   ├── joystick.dart         # Movement controller
│   ├── leaderboard.dart      # Ranking display
│   └── game_over_overlay.dart # Game over UI
└── services/
    └── storage_service.dart  # Local storage (SharedPreferences)
```

## Core Game Mechanics (from [index.html](mdc:index.html))
- **Movement**: Virtual joystick controls player movement
- **Combat**: Blade collision system with damage dealing
- **AI Behaviors**: 
  - Scout: Scavenger behavior, seeks collectibles
  - Brute: Standard aggressive behavior
  - Hunter: Charging behavior when stronger than player
- **Progression**: Collect blades to increase power and size
- **Physics**: Magnetic pickup system for nearby collectibles

## Development Guidelines

### Models ([README.md](mdc:README.md) Section 3)
- Use plain Dart classes without external annotations
- Include computed properties (e.g., `get speed`, `get bladesRadius`)
- Implement behavior methods (e.g., `takeClashDamage()`, `die()`)

### State Management
- Use single StatefulWidget (GameScreen) as state center
- AnimationController for game loop
- All game objects stored in lists (enemies, collectables, particles)
- setState() called at end of each game tick

### Rendering Strategy
- CustomPaint for game world rendering
- Transform.translate for camera movement
- Stack for UI layering (game world + HUD)
- Efficient drawing with canvas operations

### Performance Optimizations
- Use const constructors where possible
- Implement ListView.builder for long lists
- Optimize collision detection with spatial partitioning if needed
- Efficient particle system management

### UI Components
- Joystick: GestureDetector-based virtual controls
- Leaderboard: Real-time ranking display
- Game Over: Modal overlay with restart functionality
- All UI components should be stateless when possible

## Key Implementation Notes

### From HTML Game Analysis ([index.html](mdc:index.html))
- Game runs at 60fps with requestAnimationFrame equivalent
- Camera follows player with lerp smoothing (factor: 0.08)
- Magnetic pickup radius: 150px with force falloff
- Clash cooldown: 200ms between damage ticks
- Enemy spawn interval: 3000ms, max 25 enemies
- Collectable spawn rate: 1000ms, max 120 collectables

### Flutter-Specific Adaptations
- Replace DOM manipulation with CustomPainter
- Use Offset for 2D positioning instead of x/y objects
- Implement proper widget lifecycle management
- Handle touch input through GestureDetector
- Use SharedPreferences for high score persistence

## Error Handling
- Display errors using SelectableText.rich (not SnackBar)
- Graceful degradation when game objects become invalid
- Proper cleanup of animation controllers and resources

## Testing Strategy
- Unit tests for all model classes
- Widget tests for UI components
- Integration tests for game mechanics
- Performance testing for rendering pipeline

## Platform Considerations
- Ensure responsive design across different screen sizes
- Optimize for both iOS and Android performance
- Handle device rotation and safe areas
- Consider battery optimization for continuous gameplay
